County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
September 6 at 5:00 PM ·

People most vulnerable to hot weather are those who are spend a lot of time outdoors, those without air conditioning, young children, the elderly, and those with chronic ailments. We encourage our residents to check in frequently with neighbors who are older adults and those with chronic conditions who are especially vulnerable to the heat using the phone, Facetime, or Zoom to protect against spread of COVID-19. If you see someone who may be having a reaction to the heat, call 911. For more info on hot weather preparedness, visit: https://bit.ly/heatsafetytipsSCC.

post_text:
*Extreme Heat/Spare the Air Day*

Per the Mayo Clinic, "Dehydration occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions. If you don't replace lost fluids, you will get dehydrated. Anyone may become dehydrated, but the condition is especially dangerous for young children and older adults.

Thirst isn't always a reliable early indicator of the body's need for water. Many people, particularly older adults, don't feel thirsty until they're already dehydrated. That's why it's important to increase water intake during hot weather or when you're ill."

Hydrate. Drink Water. Stay Well.

California ISO issued a Flex Alert for the state amid an approaching heat wave, asking Californians to conserve power in an effort to avoid rolling blackouts over Labor Day weekend.

The Flex Alert is in effect Saturday through Monday, from 3 p.m. to 9 p.m. each day.

Tips:
> Set your air conditioner to 78° or higher, if health permits
> Use major appliances before 3:00 p.m.
> Turn off all unnecessary lights
> Tilt blinds up and close drapes and shades on windows that receive direct sunlight.
> Enable "power management" on all computers and turn off when not in use

County of Santa Clara Public Health Department
September 2 at 7:30 PM ·

California has moved to a new colored tier system to help monitor and slow the spread of COVID-19. This “Blueprint for a Safer Economy” has four Risk Levels that describe each county’s risk for COVID-19 and sets restrictions for businesses and activities in that county. Santa Clara County is currently at the Purple Risk Level. Purple means that for many of us, things will generally remain the same in addition to hair salons resuming indoor service, limited indoor retail, and more. To move to the next phase, we need to continue to protect ourselves and others to help slow the spread of COVID-19.

Each county is assigned a color based on two criteria:

➡️ Case rate
➡️ Positivity rate

Learn about the Blueprint: https://covid19.ca.gov/safer-economy/

County of Santa Clara, California
August 19 at 6:20 PM ·

EVACUATION RESOURCES UPDATE (8/19, 6:20 pm): Information hotline and website available for Santa Clara County residents seeking resource information for evacuees of #SCULightningComplex fires.

Hotline: 408-808-7778 - evacuees ONLY, not for general fire information
General fire information: http://bit.ly/LightningComplex-SCC.

An evacuation resource center at the Milpitas Library is also available for affected residents. The resource center is staffed by the American Red Cross and serves to assess the needs of individuals and families impacted by the evacuations and determine appropriate resources. It is not a shelter but serves to assist residents with temporary relocation. The Milpitas Library is located at 160 N. Main St., Milpitas.

All residents under an evacuation order are urged to take rapid action and leave the area immediately ahead of the fast-moving and unpredictable wildfire.

shared_text:
County of Santa Clara OEM
August 19 at 8:53 PM ·

不健康的空氣品質：由於煙霧的關係，聖塔克拉拉縣目前的空氣品質非常不健康。煙霧會刺激眼睛和呼吸道，引起咳嗽，造成喉嚨乾癢和刺激鼻腔。和預防新冠肺炎類似的預防措施，也能幫助我們對抗糟糕的空氣品質。有呼吸系統問題的人對空氣中的煙塵特別容易受到影響，必須更小心避免暴露在煙塵中。空氣品質可能一時改善或是很快又變糟，可以上網站 airnow.gov 查詢您附近的空氣品質。
⁣
保護您自己免受煙霧及新冠的威脅： ⁣
⁣
➡️ 盡可能的待在室內，將窗戶及門關上，直到煙霧退散。在空氣品質不健康的情況下減少出門。

➡️ 在公共空間。戴上面罩保護自己和他人免受 COVID威脅。

➡️ 減少在戶外的活動時間。

➡️ 把冷氣和車內的通氣閥調成循環，避免外面的空氣進到裡面。

➡️ 新冠檢測站會持續開放。找尋離您最近的檢測站：www.sccfreetest.org
⁣
Milpitas 圖書館 (地址：160 N. Main Street) 做為疏散資源中心，從星期三下午五點開始，開放給聖塔克拉拉居民使用。這個地點不是庇護所，但是是做為居民的臨時搬遷點。 ⁣
⁣
聖縣緊急行動中心的野火專線為：408-808-7778 ⁣
⁣
疏散資訊網站： http://bit.ly/LightningComplex-SCC

What do you want to tell or ask adults who are making the decisions that have changed your lives so dramatically over the past few months?

• What do think about going to school—or not—in the middle of a pandemic? Students
• How have students been managing remote learning?
• What thoughts or worries do students have about social distancing?
• How have protests and social unrest affected students?
Adults are encouraged to share this rare opportunity with the students in their lives and to listen in on this important conversation.

It's Kinetic Sand Day!

Sensory play can build nerve connections in the brain's pathways, which will help complete more complex learning tasks. It fosters imaginative play and encourages creativity in a relaxed way.

Playing with kinetic sand can support fine motor skills. Some may find it calming and relaxing and assists with anxiety or frustration.

You can make your own kinetic sand at home! Many recipes are available, including the one linked here. Have fun!

post_text:
Make S’mores with a solar oven!

Make a delicious snack and learn about solar energy at the same time!

Solar ovens are designed to absorb more heat than it releases; they use light and heat from the sun to cook food. This experiment can be done with other types of food! Try making nachos with tortilla chips and shredded cheese, or English muffin pizzas.

We encourage you to post your ovens in the comments below!
#WeAreSCCOE

https://climatekids.nasa.gov/smores/

County Supervisor Susan Ellenberg
August 10 at 9:25 AM ·

YOU ARE INVITED to participate in a Schools Reopening Q&A Forum on Friday, August 14 at 3:30pm hosted by me and Supervisor Cindy Chavez. This forum will be joined by Santa Clara County Office of Education Superintendent of Schools, Dr. MaryAnn Dewan, County of Santa Clara Public Health Department Director, Dr. Sara Cody, and Santa Clara County Assistant Public Health Director, Dr. Monika Roy.

This Forum is intended to be a space for questions around schools reopening to be asked and answered. Please register for the Forum here: https://bit.ly/AugSchoolsForum

We will be taking questions prior to Forum to maximize our efficiency in answering frequently asked questions and to ensure the public has up-to-date accurate answers. You can submit your questions on this registration form (linked above) or through our google form here: https://bit.ly/Questions4Schools.

Please share this message and the registration link. Thank you in advance for joining us on August 14th at 3:30pm.

post_text:
The school year is upon us! Welcome back!

School districts have been working diligently to prepare strong and engaging distance learning models for the 2020-2021 school year. Excited to welcome staff and students, the SCCOE and its districts are committed to providing current resources and updates that inform, connect, and engage Santa Clara County communities.

We value and appreciate everyone’s support, patience, and understanding as we all adjust to the new processes and protocols this school year requires. Questions and concerns will continue to arise regarding the 2020-2021 school year and we encourage students, families, and caregivers to connect directly with their respective districts and schools for information.

SCCOE kicked off the 2020-2021 school year with a landmark Pride Flag Raising Ceremony, Monday, August 3, at 10:00 a.m. on Facebook Live. The virtual Pride Flag Raising at the SCCOE’s Ridder Park office aired on the SCCOE’s Facebook Page and marked the first time the SCCOE has raised the Pride Flag. The flag's permanent installation celebrates 50 years of the SCCOE's advocacy of the LGBTQ community and underscores its "Stronger Together" commitment.

post_text:
Free COVID-19 testing is available for the community TUESDAYS through FRIDAYS, 10:00a.m. – 4:00p.m. (No testing on 8/5). Testing is open to residents of Santa Clara County at the Ridder Park office. Protocols and precautions will be in place to minimize any risk to staff members and community.

Wristbands will be distributed for an hourlong timeslot later in the day; this significantly reduces the amount of time that must be spent on site. *The supply of wristbands depends on the number of available tests and are only available as supplies last.* The County advises those interested in a test go earlier in the day rather than later to pick up a wristband. When the wristbands run out, people will be directed to other testing options nearby.

Questions regarding testing should be directed to the Santa Clara County Public Health Department .

#WeAreSCCOE #strongertogether

City of San Jose Flash Alert:

All Fireworks Are Illegal In San Jose
From the City of San José: “As the Fourth of July approaches, the City of San José and Santa Clara County Fire Department would like to remind residents that all types of fireworks, even those labeled 'safe and sane,' are illegal in San José and most of Santa Clara County. Fireworks are dangerous and can result in easily preventable fires and injuries. Residents will incur fines for using, possessing, storing, or selling illegal fireworks. Santa Clara County’s ‘social host’ Fireworks Ordinance also holds property owners responsible for illegal use of fireworks on their property.”

For more information: https://www.sanjoseca.gov/Home/Components/News/News/1511/

And never forget, no matter how overwhelming life's challenges and problems seem to be, that one person can make a difference in the world. In fact, it is always because of one person that all the changes that matter in the world come about. So be that one person." ~ R. Buckminster Fuller

post_text:
Celebrate Juneteenth today!

June 19th is the oldest known celebration of the ending of slavery. It was on this day in 1865, more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1, 1863, that Union soldiers arrived in Galveston, Texas to announce the Civil War had ended and the enslaved were free.

Freedom, Resilience, and Hope today, tomorrow, and everyday. #juneteenth #WeAreSCCOE

*Exciting News Coming Soon*

We are pleased to announce that, through a Request for Application process with the California Department of Education, the SCCOE has been awarded the contract to represent Santa Clara County as the lead agency for the Child Care Resource and Referral (R&R) services program.

Beginning July 1, 2020, we look forward to delivering much needed services to the children & families of Santa Clara County. Our goals include:
> Every family in Santa Clara County will have access to the information required to access high-quality early care and education (ECE); and
> ECE providers within the county will have access to an R&R system that supports both their programmatic and financial success.

More details & information will be shared as it becomes available.

Please take 10 minutes out of your day to complete the #2020Census online (https://my2020census.gov/), by phone (844-330-2020), or by mail. Data from the Census impacts California's representation in Congress, as well as the distribution of federal funding for programs related to schools, housing, health, and more. These programs are important for ALL communities, especially those with multiple intersecting identities that are underserved. Please join us and get counted today. #census #becounted #everyonecounts #WeAreSCCOE

Please join us and get counted today. #census #becounted #everyonecounts #WeAreSCCOE

post_text:
The benefits of coloring, for adults and youth, reach far and wide! Coloring helps to improve mood, enhance mindfulness, and reduce mental health stress. It allows our attention to shift away from ourselves and focus on the present moment, and specific task at hand. A low stakes activity, coloring is pleasurable and relaxes our brains; it doesn’t need to be predictable or prescriptive. Coloring can be as neat, or as messy, as you choose - one of its relaxing perks.

To close out today's #WellnessWednesday, we turn to our friends at the Santa Clara County Office of LGBTQ Affairs. Their Kids Activity Book is wonderful for all ages. Created by, and based on the art, books, and work of Maya Gonzalez - Author & Artist, this booklet allows children and their families/chosen families to color and read shorts stories that will help explore and celebrate the unique LGBTQ presence in nature, community, and more!

Follow the link to enjoy - https://bit.ly/activitycoloringbook

#SCCOEPride

post_text:
Pride is a celebration; it is the freedom, beauty and joy that comes from simply being you. In fact, the term “pride” is very purposeful. Its meaning counteracts the feelings of shame, guilt, and stigma that is often associated with LGBTQ+ identifying people.

For today’s #FunFriday, we wanted to bring the freedom, beauty and joy to you in the form of an arts and craft project, enjoyable for kids AND adults. For kids? Crafts nurture their creativity, help to boost self esteem, & encourages self-expression.

Something to remember: There is more than one way to approach an activity. Don’t worry if the materials differ from the ones shown in this video, or about "being correct". Focus on the experience; explore and create! Most importantly...enjoy yourself.

For the demonstration video: bit.ly/prideballoonvideo

If you would like an instruction sheet for the craft demonstrated in the video, please visit https://bit.ly/prideballoon.

#SCCOEPride #WeAreSCCOE

post_text:
In the wake of traumatic events, it can be difficult for adults to know how to help children understand and cope. Comfort, support and reassurance can make a child feel safe. The presence and engagement of trusted adults and other persons help young people manage fears, maneuver through sorrow, and help build skills on how to recover in healthy ways.

Here are some tips on how to support young people, while also looking out for our own wellness. Please note: If you or your children require assistance from a mental health professional, do not hesitate to ask a doctor or other health care provider for assistance.

For the full document - visit : https://bit.ly/10tips2help

#TuesdayTip

post_text:
Welcome to June and #PrideMonth!

Pride is about acceptance, celebration, love, and reflection, and the SCCOE would like to wish everyone in the LGBTQ+ community a joyful June!

Because of the Covid-19 pandemic, this year’s Pride will look very different across the globe. However, no stranger to crises, Pride is not just about celebration. It’s a movement that emerged after the Stonewall Riots in 1969.

Follow this month’s SCCOE social media posts as we work to address some of the specific needs of the LGBTQ+ community during this pandemic, and reaffirm the need for fair representation. Resilience and determination is inspirational, as is strength, intentionality, and proactiveness.

#WeAreSCCOE #SCCOEPride

Visualizing Social Distancing: On 5/18/20, “County of Santa Clara Health Officer Dr. Sara Cody announced amendments to the current Shelter in Place Order to allow some businesses to resume operating, with modifications based on significant progress in controlling the spread of COVID-19.” While continuing to stay at home is the best course of action, keep in mind social distancing and face coverings are still expected when out in public. To help visualize 6ft, which is the minimum suggested distancing, the list below may help the separation - especially with kids!

Twin size bed
Two yardsticks glued together tip to tip
A yoga mat
A ladder
Dog leash
A MacBook Air charger
Height of a standard door
Standard sedan car
3 seat sofa/couch
Height of a standard refrigerator

What other comparisons can you think of? Share in the comments below -

post_text:
It's Classified Employee Week! (May 17-23, 2020)

Classified staff often work outside of the classroom and support the education of our students behind the scenes - front offices, food service, buildings & rounds and building, and so much more.

The commitment of our classified employees can be invisible to the community; but, they are our unsung heroes that enable other staff focus on teaching and learning. Without the dedication of our support staff, our schools could not function appropriately.

Thank you!

post_text:
Today is The International Day of Families.

Founded by the United Nations in 1994, The International Day of Families is observed on annually, on May 15th. It’s a day to celebrate the importance of families, people, societies and cultures around the world.

There are several different types of families with diverse structures, beliefs, cultural norms, and personal practices. Related, or not, a family is a group of people who love and trust one another. Family members might not have been there from day one; It doesn’t matter what chapter of your story they entered. Once present, hearts are open, and love is unconditional.

Today, and everyday, let's celebrate diversity of families, encourage inclusion, & accept one another. #WeAreSCCOE

Photo used with permission - Elise Gravel - français

Although a day late, we didn't want to let The California Day of the Teacher pass without acknowledgement. California Day of the Teacher is recognized on the second Wednesday in May; it celebrates educators across our state. This is a perfect opportunity for all Californians to take a moment to remember, and honor, all the individuals who gave/give the gift of knowledge through teaching.

Now, more than ever, as teachers pivot quickly to distance learning while figuring out how best to serve their students, The California Day of the Teacher is especially important.

Thank you teachers, for all you do, each and every day.

#WeAreSCCOE

Lemon water is a relatively inexpensive drink that helps the human body and mind. A tasty alternative to plain water or sugary drinks, it has many health benefits to offer, including the following:

Lemon Water promotes hydration, is a good source of vitamin C, improves your skin quality, aids digestion, freshens breath, and helps prevent kidney stones.

It's Reading is Fun Week!

There are countless benefits to reading, individually, and with others, in any language! Some benefits to reading include, but are not limited to (1) sharpens your mind (2) increases your vocabulary, (3) lowers stress, (4) improves your memory and focus, (5) strengthens your writing abilities, and (6) enhances your imagination.

What's your favorite thing to read? Books, magazines, online stories?

#WeAreSCCOE

post_text:
#TuesdayTip: Talking to Kids about the Coronavirus

Wondering how to discuss the coronavirus with children, of all ages, in a reassuring way that will not increase worry? Dr. Jamie Howard: senior clinical psychologist in the Anxiety Disorders Center; and Director of Trauma and Resilience Service at the Child Mind Institute, offers some practical advice for all of us.

• Don’t be afraid to discuss the coronavirus.
• Be developmentally appropriate.
• Take your cues from your child.
• Deal with your own anxiety.
• Be reassuring.
• Focus on what you’re doing to stay safe.
• Stick to routine.
• Keep talking (i.e. provide regular updates).

http://ow.ly/gM6I50zp0xS

#WeAreSCCOE

Positive affirmations are words, phrases or mantras we use to repeat to ourselves. They describe a specific outcome or who you want to be and prime our brains for change. At first, these affirmations might not be true, but with constant repetition, your subconscious mind will start to believe them. And eventually, these affirmations will become your reality.

Look at the grid below. Some say the first three words you see best describe you. What do you think? #WellnessWednesday #WeAreSCCOE

5. Color a picture/a rainbow

The American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (ASPCA) was founded in New York City in 1866? Or,

The Great Gatsby by F. Scott Fitzgerald was first published 1925?

Have a wonderfully safe and healthy weekend, everyone!

post_text:
It's #WellnessWednesday!

For today's wellness focus, we invite you to make a Happiness & Gratitude Jar. Find an empty jar that will help you see this shelter-in-place through until its end. (A cup or resealable bag will work, as well.)

Take time for yourself, every day, to write down something that made you happy, grateful, appreciative, etc. Place your note into your jar. Whenever you want or need, open the jar and read all the amazing things that made you smile.

Your personal Happiness & Gratitude Jar will provide an opportunity to pause for mindful reflection. It is important to take hold of the the spirit of living, celebrate life, and capture memories. Five minutes a day is all it takes to make note of the rainbows in your life, rather than thunderstorms.

#WeAreSCCOE

post_text:
How are you staying productive and mentally healthy while working/schooling during the shelter-in-place? Here are some tips that many of our staff are finding useful. What strategies have been helpful for you? Share your tips in the comments below!

• Get dressed for the day; Don’t start the work day in your PJs, no matter how tempting it may be!
• Create a schedule; Take short breaks; Exercise & stretch regularly
• Eat healthy lunch & snacks
• Set up a designated work space, preferably not in the living or bedroom
• Set working hours; Discover your high productivity time-periods
• Invest in a good pair of headphones
• Make to-do lists
• Limit social media time

#WeAreSCCOE #TuesdayTip

April 7 at 8:15 AM ·

Volunteers at Santa Clara County Office of Education have been sharing their time with us assembling family activity kits that will soon be distributed to Family Resource Centers. Update: Thank you so much for your interest in the activity kits. Please note that the kits are still being assembled and the distribution phase of the kits to the Family Resource Centers is also a work in progress. More updates to follow.

post_text:
County of Santa Clara Public Health Department has shared a video regarding face coverings, following the state public health department’s statement this week. Please take a moment to watch the video. *Important: This is a recommendation, not an order.*

To access the County of Santa Clara Public Health Department press release, visit: bit.ly/SCCPHfacemask

In summary:
• Use cloth face coverings, not masks (save surgical/medical and N95 masks for healthcare workers, first responders, etc.)
• Face coverings are intended to limit the spread by individuals with/without symptoms
• Face coverings protect those coming into contact with you--evidence suggests that individuals can be asymptomatic for 48 hours before symptom onset.
• Use face covering when performing any essential activity
• Cover nose and mouth
• Wash the face covering frequently
• Wash your hands after you've touched your mask

post_text:
@SCCOE has partnered with My Green Lunch to provide families in need with fresh, nutritious meals that are easy to heat and eat. To learn more visit: https://bit.ly/3dKBzSg

Like many businesses, My Green Lunch has been significantly impacted by the COVID-19 health crisis. In response, their team has shifted their production focus to solely providing safe and nutritious “sealed meals” to the homeless, elderly, sick, first responders and children in the Bay Area. Diligent with following FDA and state health codes and Covid-19 prevention practices, My Green Lunch works to produce 3,000-5,000 meals a day. With a goal of providing up to 60,000 meals over the course of the shelter in place, community support is appreciated, as they look to raise $300,000 to provide hit their target number of meals. For more information, visit the My Green Lunch fundraising page: http://bit.ly/MyGreenLunch. #WeAreSCCOE

post_text:
The Shelter-In-Place order means school is closed to student attendance until April 3rd. Are you a teacher, parent or student in need of online resources?

Check out the SCCOE newly launched SCCOE/COVID-19
web page! sccoe.org/covid-19

This community resource portal features read-alouds, virtual field trips, and websites that support learning math, history and language arts, as well as guidance for how to facilitate online learning for teachers and many other flexible learning options for preschool through 12th grade students.

There's also information on how parents can access a 16-hour daily warmline with educational support in English, Spanish, Vietnamese, Mandarin, and Korean.

For the latest information about support and resources for teachers, students and families during Shelter-In-Place, visit: sccoe.org/covid-19/
